count - number of loops to complete
reset - If true, then the counter will restart counting from the beginning.

This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:

ab6666ce-5536-4ac7-92dd-5acb5f698e8a.38c90a22-34be-47bb-911f-dc92e70e769f.description=
Sends an smtp email
 
Input Parameters\:
hostname - hostname or ip address of smtp server
port - port smtp service is listening
from - from email address
to - email address(s) or recipients
subject - email subject
body - body of the email
htmlEmail - true or false, whether the email should be sent supporting html rich email.
readReceipt - true or false, whether or not to request a read receipt
attachments - comma separated list of files to attach (must be full path)
username - if SMTP authentication is needed, the username to send
password - the password to use
characterSet - the character set encoding for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is UTF-8
contentTransferEncoding - the content transfer encoding scheme (such as 7bit, 8bit, base64, quoted-printable etc) for the entire email which includes subject, body, attached file name and the attached file. Default value is - quoted-printable or Q Encoding.
 
 Responses\:
 success - successfully sent the email
 failure - failed to send the email

Note\:
For special characters (East Asian, right-to-left languages, etc.) you must install the support files on your local machine.
	For doing this on Windows go to Control Panel -> Regional and Language Options -> Language and check the options at Supplemental language support.

Internally this flow will use ssh for the protocol and port 2222 for the connection. Inputs\: coreHost - SAS core hostname or IP address coreUsername - SAS username to access the coreHost corePassword - SAS user's password to access the coreHost serverName - name of the managed server to be deactivated Responses\: success - operation completed successfully failure - otherwise ab6666ce-5536-4ac7-92dd-5acb5f698e8a.3c72cc45-a3b2-485f-8399-9ac4ce937c93.description=
Compares two strings, returning a true response if and only if they contain the same sequence of characters. A null string is considered to be equal to an empty string.

Inputs\:
string1 - The first string.
string2 - The second string.
ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. The two strings are considered equal ignoring case if they are of the same length and corresponding characters in the two strings are equal ignoring case. If set to any value other than 'true', then the strings must match exactly to be considered equal.

responses\:
true - If the two strings are equal
false - If the two strings are not equal
ab6666ce-5536-4ac7-92dd-5acb5f698e8a.40801200-e33f-44ff-b4d2-1d760cb9319c.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

ab6666ce-5536-4ac7-92dd-5acb5f698e8a.70347e17-5803-4100-97fb-77fba572eff8.description=
Scan opened ports on give host  

Inputs\: 
 host - IP address Host name to be scanned
 lowestPort - lowest port range
 highestPort - highest port range
 portType - the type of ports to be scanned (TCP or UDP). If not specified, the TCP ports are scanned.

Note\:
 To scan specific port give same port as parameter for both Lowest Port and Highest Port, 

Responses\:
 success - the command was executed successfully
 failure - the command could not be executed

Result\:
 finalResult - Information about the ports' statuses on a given machine.

Extra results\:
 host - the IP of the host for which the ports are scanned
 ports - Number of ports scanned
 opened - Number of ports open
 closed - Number of ports closed
 dropped - Number of ports dropped

ab6666ce-5536-4ac7-92dd-5acb5f698e8a.7db780eb-b557-4bce-8255-d0afca634683.description=Starts deploying an agent on an unmanaged server. This operation is supported from SA version 10.1 (sas101). Inputs\: coreHost - The DNS name or IP Address of your SAS core. corePort - The port to connect to your SAS core on. coreProtocol - The protocol to connect to your SAS core with. Either HTTP or HTTPS. coreUsername - The username for host. corePassword - The password for host. coreVersion - The version of SAS to use. serverIPAddress - The IP address of the server on which the agent will be installed. protocol - Set the protocol used to login to the server on which the agent will be installed. If set to 'Select automatically', the job will try every protocol possible and use the first which is available. Possible values are\: ssh, telnet, netbt, rlogin. protocolPort - Set the port for the protocol specified above. If not set, the default port for the protocol will be used. username - The username for the server on which the agent will be installed. password - The password for the server on which the agent will be installed. rootPassword - Specify in case authentication is done as a non-root user, to become root (UNIX only). Set the value 'sudo' if the user is in the sudoers group, otherwise set the root password. actionType - Select the action type\: 'check' for checking if prerequisite conditions are fulfilled, 'download' for checking if prerequisite conditions are fulfilled and staging(downloading) the Agent installer binary or 'install' for checking if the prerequisite conditions are fulfilled, staging(downloading) the Agent installer binary and running the Agent installer binary. Default is 'install'. targetOSClass - Set the target OS class for the server on which the agent will be installed. Valid values are\: Windows, UNIX. realmName - The name of the realm. If set, the gateway inputs will be ignored. realmID - The ID of the realm. If set, the 'realmName' and the gateway inputs will be ignored. gatewayName - The name of the gateway. If set, the 'gatewayAddressInfo' must be specified. gatewayID - The ID of the gateway. If set, the 'gatewayAddressInfo' must be specified and the 'gatewayName' will be ignored. gatewayAddressInfo - The IP addresses and proxy ports of the gateways, in the format \:, separated by 'separator'. The IP addresses can be either version 4 (e.g. 192.168.55.22\:100) or version 6, which must be enclosed in brackets (e.g. [ff\:\:]\:100). If set, the gateway name or ID must be specified. noStartAgent - Do not start agent after installation. Default value is false. ignorePrerequisiteCheckFailures - Specify whether the deployment process should ignore any prerequisites check failures and proceed with the Agent installation. Default value is false. setTime - Set system time from HP Server Automation core. Default value is false. installMSI - Install Windows installer (MSI) if required (Windows only). Default value is false. reboot - Reboot at completion of successful install if warranted (Windows only). Default value is false. installRPM - Install Red Hat Package Manager (RPM) if required (AIX/Solaris only). Default value is false. resetConf - Reset agent configuration file to default settings. Default value is false. noOpswareGateway - Indicate that no Opsware gateway is necessary. Default value is false. overwriteInstaller - Specify whether HP SA Agent installer binary should be overwritten in case already staged. Default value is false. logLevel - The log level. Log levels are\: error, trace, warning, info. Default value is error. forceFullHardwareRegistration - Force full hardware registration. Default value is false. forceSoftwareRegistration - Force software registration. Default value is false. noReachabilityCheck - Suppress agent reachability check. Default value is false. noAnonymousSSL - Disable anonymous SSL. Applies to dormant agent only. Default value is false. forceNewDevice - Force creation of new device record if conflict found. Default value is false. failOnHardwareRegistrationError - Fail if initial hardware registration fails (do not go dormant). Default value is false. doNotOpenWindowsFirewall - Set 'true' to not open Windows firewall for core-agent communications. Default value is false. remediateSoftwarePolicy - Perform a remediate of Software Policies after install. Default value is false. softwarePolicyID - The ID of the software policy to attach. fingerprint - Fingerprint of the peer's certificate. Default value is false. installerOptions - Set the command line arguments for the HP SA Agent installer. userTag - An user provided tag applicable to this job. timeout - The maximum time, in seconds, within which this method should complete and the operation should return. The job will fail with a timeout error if the Install HP SA Agent operation does not complete in the given number of seconds. The default value is 0 (no timeout). separator - The separator used for separating the inputs. The default value for the separator is a comma (,). notificationFailureOwner - The email address of the owner of the job when the job failed. notificationSuccessOwner - The email address of the owner of the job when the job succeeded. notificationCancelOwner - The email address of the owner of the job when the job was canceled. notificationFailureRecipients - The email addresses to notify when the job failed. notificationSuccessRecipients - The email addresses to notify when the job succeeded. notificationCancelRecipients - The email addresses to notify when the job was canceled. scheduleDateYear - The year to be used for setting the date when the job is scheduled to start. This input must be provided for setting a job schedule. scheduleDateMonth - The month to be used for setting the date when the job is scheduled to start. It should have the value between 1 and 12. This input must be provided for setting a job schedule. scheduleDateDayOfMonth - The day to be used for setting the date when the job is scheduled to start. It should have the value between 1 and 31. This input must be provided for setting a job schedule. scheduleDateHour - The hour to be used for setting the date when the job is scheduled to start. It should have the value between 0 and 23. If not set, if will have the default value 0. scheduleDateMinute - The minute to be used for setting the date when the job is scheduled to start. It should have the value between 0 and 59. If not set, if will have the default value 0. scheduleDateSecond - The second to be used for setting the date when the job is scheduled to start. It should have the value between 0 and 59. If not set, if will have the default value 0. scheduleDateTimezone - The time zone used to express the job schedule date. If not set, it will have the default value GMT. Outputs\: jobId - The ID of the job created for installing a HP SA Agent on a server. Responses\: success - The operation has completed successfully. failure - The operation has failed. ab6666ce-5536-4ac7-92dd-5acb5f698e8a.90fc8548-e641-448d-8d32-49fea21748ef.description=Sleeps for "X" seconds.

    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Uses WMI to attempt to create a remote process on a machine.  The command passed should be formatted as though it was run on the command line.

CAUTION\: internally 'cmd /c' gets prepended to the command passed.  Also '2>tempfile 1>tempfile' get appended to the command so that we can attempt to capture stdout and stderr.
So your command will look like this when executed\:
	'cmd /c [yourcommand] 2>temperr 1>tempout'

Inputs\:
host - Hostname or ip address of the target machine.
command - The command you want executed.
user - Username to use for remote WMI impersonation and thread impersonation on the RAS host for this operation (can be left blank).
password - Password of the user.
outputPath - Network accessible path used by the operation to store temporary files. If not specified it points to \\host\admin$\temp\'. If this path is not accessible you should change it to use another share that the host local system account has write access to. By default the path will have to be changed on Windows 2000 systems.
currentDirectory - Current directory.
characterSet - The character encoding used to write the batch file that will be remotely executed by the operation (for instance\: ibm437, shift_jis).  Unicode character encodings may not supported for this input (utf-8, utf-16, etc.).  Support for unicode encodings depends on target system capabilities.  By default this encoding will also be used to read the command output that is redirected to temporary files.  If the command output is expected to be of different encoding, specify the different encoding in the outputCharacterSet input.  The default value is the default encoding of the RAS.
outputCharacterSet - The character encoding used to read the command output that was redirected to temporary files.  Only need to specify this input if the output of the command is known to output a different character encoding.  As an example\: the 'wmic' command returns utf-16 encoded output.  Examples of valid inputs include\: ibm437, shift_jis, utf-8, utf-16.
timeout - The number of seconds before assuming the remote process is no longer functional.  After the timeout has expired the remote process and all child processes will be terminated.  the default value is 600.

Responses\:
success - Remote process successfully launched and has completed executing.
failure - Unable to start remote process.

Extra Results\:
ReturnValue - Return value from WMI for starting the process (not the exit value of the process).
ProcessID - The process id of the remote process.
ProcessReturnCode - The return code of the remote process.
StdOut - Standard output from the remote process.
StdErr - Standard error from the remote process.

Notes\: 
List of possible encoding names (Support for the encoding may depend on the version or language of the RAS OS)\:
